comment:
So much for the victim part when the defensive is more elaborate than the actual crime proclaimed. "He hurt me" -"But didn't you hurt him too?" -"OH well see, yes, no, about that *starts chewing massive candy* ... *inaudible* ...". Let my softie boy johnny out yo. lol. I know what he been thru I had a toxic ex. Now its my girls who have to suffer her. 

Reality is any true victim will not fight back. Period. Any good cop knows that. Every ignorant snowflake doesn't get it. All you need is the proof she was violent as well. case closed. In 7 years living with my babymama I had countless pictures of my face scratches, pulled hair, conversations with her mom locked inside the bathroom as she's trying to break in to keep hitting me as I refuse to fight a woman... ect ... ect...

She called the cops on me one day saying I tried to kill her, no wounds, nothing. (I was breaking up and didn't want to just leave all my belongings and house, I'm 6 ft and Ive worked with my hands all my career, trust me if I want to choke something it's either gone or has markings something, even the arresting cops agreed, as they came with the swat to collect me, at a friend's house that I had disclosed the address after calling the cops to leave the house) 

They robbed my kids away from me and stole my life for 9 months before I could have my trial and show my evidence. Case was closed next hearing. Acquitted. Had I not been documenting her violence? I'd be dead today. I also won my custody after countless court battles and even agreeing to pay alimony on a shared 50/50 custody. But the damage was already there and they never removed the bad labels. Yet she's the one who was punching me @ 4 am holding my 6 month old baby over the bathtub to she could vomit the rest of her bad night. She was angry I wasn't apologetic about waking her up. Punched me right on the side of the head as I was holding my baby girl. And she's the one with all the gracious mom labels while I'm the toxic dad. Ask my girls who they want to be with. You won't even have time to finish your sentence. "DAAAAADDDY! ALLLLLLLL the time!" (yeah because they already ripped in 2 with time share). 

And I've been a terrible dad. barely 20 to 50% of what I could have been if I had a real wife instead of a toxic gobblin completely blinded by alcohol, peer pressure and social media. Victimising their way to success in life supported by government while she destroys family patrimony. The money wasted alone could put our girls through private high school. I'm only still around to make sure my daughters don't end up victims of this systematic corruption of our youth especially our young girls. Once they're good to go I'm out this B y'all can enjoy your societies of hypocrisy. I've been ready to die ever since the 3rd week they took my girls away from me. Only woke up from the abyss 6 months later. Reborn. To me these 6 months lasted forever, a lifetime. I was not eating, drinking or doing any drugs. Nothing much but being lost in this pain inside of me. Waking up crying, exhausting myself mentally and still crying to sleep. Spaced out of my body, hidding in the darkness. Talking to my soul. Trying to solve an existential problem.

 Trust me, we don't see the same world out there today ;) 

I only truly prayed twice in my life... both times I told this entity up there, that I was coming over, not asking for anything you know, just giving a courtesy heads up, that was it for me. You know what happened both times? I just woke up the next day with a new joy for life. Because it just isn't my time yet, I'm just ready for it. Whenever. Wherever. I'm at peace with death and I now accept it as my deliverance. It has released me from their hypnosis and that's why, even tho good, we will remain black sheeps in this world. Stay Strong Brothers. Trust god, trust your soul. For it is all and everything.

(Notice how in all of this, I am never victimising, even trying to be honest and dirty myself, that's because I understood life, the good and the wrong, the white and the black, its all one and the same, you aren't better, or worse, than the next one) Peace

comment:
I wasn't in the room with them so I don't know the truth, but this video was made from someone who clearly is one sided, what I see is a woman declaring and following her attorney instructions (the food part I don't know maybe it was a long procedure and that's why she was allowed to eat,maybe she had low sugar, I don't know what the judge allow it), both attorneys make their questions to injury the other part, at least to show their client is speaking the truth, I don't why the video says she is lying she said she did something to John when she saw her sister was going to be hurt.
I know for personal experience that in violent situations people can go "blind "and not aware of what they are doing, this doesn't make it right, I violent person is still a violent person who should have some treatment, who ever was the perpetrator in this couple, or maybe it was a toxic relationship and they were both violent , I don't know.
What I know is that when a violent person cross the line (maybe some abuse is tolerated but when he/she goes after someone something you hold dear) after a long time of experience this something in you just snap, I was the one who never was pushed or hit, and this person I'm talking about , never was to violent to make serious injuries, except to my self-esteem, my emotions, it make me grow as a fearful child, the other part in this wasn't protective of their children either, the things that came out of that violent mouth, hurt, one day when I finally saw everyone for who they are, I told him I know if you hit me you are going to hurt me because I can't beat you (I meant I can't win ) but you have to know if you ever hit me, I won't stand still I'm going to hit you back. comment:
The way she pulls up her eyebrow is a 'believe-me-face '. The eating is probably to calm her nerves, it also adds an aura of innocence as this is something a younger person would do to distract themselves in a, particularly heavy and confronting situation.  Obviously, this is all speculation but most victims do fall into a camp in how they act. This not the typical energy of domestic violence victims. There is no pain in her face. A victim would be enraged, resentful by being accused of abuse by their abuser in the court of law. They might be ashamed or holding shaky confidence to address such a heavy topic. She, however, is showing concealing energy and urgency in looking to her lawyer's advice .. a victim would want to be heard, they would want to be seen.


*again this doesn't speak for every single victim, but in every victim, there is a glimpse, an aura of abuse written on their face and body that is deeper than any words that can be spoken.
